english:
  title: A Village House
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Where the blue mountains break away stand two or three houses,
    Cradled by the hills, a single path winds askew.
    The frogs croak in the pond, prophesying rain—
    The magpies chatter in the high trees, reading the wind.
    The willow-lined alley, so still and deep, lies buried in grass,
    The brushwood gate, where no one comes, lies hidden in fallen flowers.
    Wandering beyond the dusty world, I find my own delight—
    I laugh at those who hurry about chasing fleeting glories.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The poem employs natural sounds (frogs croaking, magpies chattering) as traditional omens or signs, reflecting classical Chinese cosmological beliefs about reading nature's messages.
  - key: ''
    value: The final couplet presents a philosophical contrast between the speaker's contentment in solitude and the conventional pursuit of worldly success and recognition.
